properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Potentially damaging winds tonight. An Alberta Clipper will continue to bring moderate winds gusting between 60 and 70 km/h early this evening. Winds will then strengthen later this evening with gusts up to 90 km/h. Winds will diminish Monday morning. In addition, flurries will develop off of Lake Huron and Georgian Bay this evening. Strong winds along with the falling snow will reduce visibilities at times and make travel difficult. Flurries will end early Monday morning. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. High winds may toss loose objects or cause tree branches to break. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A frontal system west of the offshore waters over the Pacific will be rapidly intensifying today as it approaches the BC coast. As the frontal system reaches the BC north and central coasts later today and overnight into Monday it rapidly moves south. By Monday afternoon the system stalls over west Vancouver Island and upwards of 100 to 150 mm of rainfall accumulation could occur through until Tuesday morning. Over the south coast, the frontal system will become entrenched overnight Monday and through until Tuesday afternoon. During that time, accumulations of 50 to 75 mm could be expected to fall over north and central metro Vancouver regions as well as Howe Sound. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
